A Tanzanian court is to sentence a 69-year-old Chinese woman for her role in trafficking tusks from more than 400 elephants, reports AFP. Yang Fenglan, dubbed the “Ivory Queen”, was convicted in Dar es Salaam of trafficking 860 tusks between 2000 and 2014, according to AFP. It says two Tanzanian men were also found guilty for their role in the illegal trade. The court has not yet announced their sentences, but Fenlan faces up to 30 years in prison, AFP says.  ‘Why illegal ivory traders  seem unstoppable’ Terror convict''s sentence doubled Foreigners convicted for ivory trafficking